	<CustomSection title={"Poetic Visions: Free Verse for a Sustainable Future"} content={"<strong>(30-60 MINUTES)</strong>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Materials:"} content={"<p>Journals, notebooks, or paper for writing<br>Pens, pencils<br>Whiteboard or projector<br>Markers</p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<Introduction content={"<p>Begin by introducing/re-introducing Global Goal 11. Briefly explain its purpose: to create cities that are inclusive, safe, resilient, and sustainable.<br>Engage students with a quick “think-pair-share” activity: What makes a city feel ‘livable’ to you?\n<ul>\n<li>Encourage students to think beyond just physical structures and consider social and environmental aspects. Examples of answer might look like:</li>\n<li><em>Social Aspects</em></li>\n<li>A place where I feel safe walking at night.</li>\n<li>A community with diverse cultures and people.</li>\n<li>Access to places where I can hang out with friends, like parks or cafes.</li>\n<li>A place that feels like it has a strong community.</li>\n<li>A place where there are opportunities for jobs and education.</li>\n<li>A place where I feel like I belong.</li>\n<li><em>Environmental Aspects</em></li>\n<li>Lots of green spaces and trees.</li>\n<li>Clean air and water.</li>\n<li>Good public transportation that reduces pollution.</li>\n<li>Places to safely ride my bike.</li>\n<li>Effective recycling and waste management.</li>\n<li>A place that is working to combat climate change.</li>\n<li><em>Physical Structures</em></li>\n<li>Affordable housing.</li>\n<li>Reliable public transportation.</li>\n<li>Good internet access.</li>\n<li>Well maintained roads and sidewalks.</li>\n<li>Access to diverse stores and restaurants.</li>\n<li>Places to engage in art, music, etc.</li>\n</ul><br>Show diverse images related to Global Goal 11. Ask students to share down initial feelings or impressions (can be done verbally as a class or written individually).<br>`\t`Examples of images:\n<ul>\n<li><em>Positive Aspects</em></li>\n<li><em>Bustling Market</em></li>\n<li>Search: “<a href=\"https://www.google.co.uk/search?sca_esv=45c41d3e543101a5&amp;q=bustling+urban+market&amp;udm=2&amp;fbs=ABzOT_CWdhQLP1FcmU5B0fn3xuWp5u5rQsC2YJafWTbyNSy6G3Vsi155b_IyTtSTnvQaXi_rq8p_LgGTTbO2VNME7iYx1le3qrn_QeGzvCQjJTmjNJQyvjgOyx1EvTA-xf1VaKvxWqQoQ87J0bKGndm_exzkLOglKNss7VwweAZTDfHn_X1-I2UMw1JPnV5u4wY7nPD2CY8-mVEv0wEZt6iAb8x_YQSC1A&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=2ahUKEwiCsKfQsJSMAxVl6ckDHbitI2AQtKgLegQIEBAB&amp;biw=1200&amp;bih=728&amp;dpr=2\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Bustling urban market</a>” or similar in image search engine</li>\n<li>Feelings: Energy, community, cultural richness, diversity.</li>\n<li><em>Green Spaces</em></li>\n<li>Search “<a href=\"https://www.google.co.uk/search?q=urban+park&amp;sca_esv=45c41d3e543101a5&amp;udm=2&amp;biw=1200&amp;bih=728&amp;ei=jcvZZ922FdLdwN4Pr7_KmQ0&amp;ved=0ahUKEwidsdbRsJSMAxXSLtAFHa-fMtMQ4dUDCBE&amp;uact=5&amp;oq=urban+park&amp;gs_lp=EgNpbWciCnVyYmFuIHBhcmsyCBAAGIAEGLEDMgUQABiABDIFEAAYgAQyBRAAGIAEMgUQABiABDIFEAAYgAQyBRAAGIAEMgUQABiABDIFEAAYgAQyBRAAGIAESLQNUP4EWPwKcAN4AJABAJgBNKAB0gOqAQIxMLgBA8gBAPgBAZgCCqAC_QPCAgoQABiABBhDGIoFwgILEAAYgAQYsQMYgwHCAg0QABiABBixAxhDGIoFwgIOEAAYgAQYsQMYgwEYigWYAwCIBgGSBwIxMKAHwzGyBwIxMLgH_QM&amp;sclient=img\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Urban park</a>” or similar in image search engine</li>\n<li>Feelings: Calmness, relaxation, connection to nature, peace.</li>\n<li><em>Efficient Public Transport</em></li>\n<li>Search “<a href=\"https://www.google.co.uk/search?q=modern+public+transit&amp;sca_esv=45c41d3e543101a5&amp;udm=2&amp;biw=1200&amp;bih=728&amp;ei=VczZZ_6OGpfLp84P593LqAc&amp;ved=0ahUKEwi-jYqxsZSMAxWX5ckDHefuEnUQ4dUDCBE&amp;uact=5&amp;oq=modern+public+transit&amp;gs_lp=EgNpbWciFW1vZGVybiBwdWJsaWMgdHJhbnNpdDIEEAAYHkj1FFCQBFjVEnADeACQAQCYAW-gAdQHqgEEMjAuMbgBA8gBAPgBAZgCGKACrQjCAgYQABgHGB7CAgoQABiABBhDGIoFwgILEAAYgAQYsQMYgwHCAggQABiABBixA8ICBRAAGIAEwgIOEAAYgAQYsQMYgwEYigXCAgYQABgFGB7CAgYQABgIGB6YAwCIBgGSBwQyMy4xoAesarIHBDIwLjG4B5sI&amp;sclient=img\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Modern public transit</a>” or similar in image search engine</li>\n<li>Feelings: Efficiency, convenience, connectivity, forward movement.</li>\n<li><em>Negative Aspects</em></li>\n<li><em>Slums/Informal Settlements</em></li>\n<li>Search “<a href=\"https://www.google.co.uk/search?q=urban+slums&amp;sca_esv=45c41d3e543101a5&amp;udm=2&amp;biw=1200&amp;bih=728&amp;ei=B83ZZ4y2Kbqrur8Psruk-QI&amp;ved=0ahUKEwjM1YmGspSMAxW6le4BHbIdKS8Q4dUDCBE&amp;uact=5&amp;oq=urban+slums&amp;gs_lp=EgNpbWciC3VyYmFuIHNsdW1zMgUQABiABDIFEAAYgAQyBRAAGIAEMgUQABiABDIFEAAYgAQyBRAAGIAEMgUQABiABDIFEAAYgAQyBRAAGIAEMgUQABiABEj7DlD2BFiJDXADeACQAQCYAT2gAYMEqgECMTG4AQPIAQD4AQGYAg6gAsIEwgIEEAAYHsICCxAAGIAEGLEDGIMBwgIIEAAYgAQYsQPCAgoQABiABBhDGIoFwgINEAAYgAQYsQMYQxiKBZgDAIgGAZIHAjE0oAf2N7IHAjExuAe2BA&amp;sclient=img\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Urban slums</a>” or similar in image search engine</li>\n<li>Feelings: Inequality, unfair, crowded, despair</li>\n<li><em>Pollution/Waste</em></li>\n<li>Search “<a href=\"https://www.google.co.uk/search?q=urban+air+pollution&amp;sca_esv=45c41d3e543101a5&amp;udm=2&amp;biw=1200&amp;bih=728&amp;ei=_s3ZZ_aAKdasur8PwKmyoAM&amp;ved=0ahUKEwj29-z7spSMAxVWlu4BHcCUDDQQ4dUDCBE&amp;uact=5&amp;oq=urban+air+pollution&amp;gs_lp=EgNpbWciE3VyYmFuIGFpciBwb2xsdXRpb24yBRAAGIAEMgUQABiABDIFEAAYgAQyBRAAGIAEMgUQABiABDIFEAAYgAQyBRAAGIAEMgUQABiABDIFEAAYgAQyBRAAGIAESPcSUMoGWKARcAJ4AJABAJgBOKABtASqAQIxM7gBA8gBAPgBAZgCD6AC8wTCAgoQABiABBhDGIoFwgIGEAAYBxgewgIIEAAYgAQYsQPCAgsQABiABBixAxiDAZgDAIgGAZIHAjE1oAfURrIHAjEzuAfrBA&amp;sclient=img\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Urban air pollution</a>” or similar in image search engine</li>\n<li>Feelings: Sadness, danger, unhealthy, anger</li>\n<li><em>Disaster Aftermath</em></li>\n<li>Search “<a href=\"https://www.google.co.uk/search?q=urban+disaster+damage&amp;sca_esv=45c41d3e543101a5&amp;udm=2&amp;biw=1200&amp;bih=728&amp;ei=ps7ZZ7PwBe-8kPIP9tS0uA4&amp;ved=0ahUKEwiz29fLs5SMAxVvHkQIHXYqDecQ4dUDCBE&amp;uact=5&amp;oq=urban+disaster+damage&amp;gs_lp=EgNpbWciFXVyYmFuIGRpc2FzdGVyIGRhbWFnZUiqFFCEAljyEXABeACQAQCYAUegAbAFqgECMTW4AQPIAQD4AQGYAgugAo8EwgIKEAAYgAQYQxiKBcICBhAAGAcYHsICBRAAGIAEwgIIEAAYgAQYsQPCAgsQABiABBixAxiKBcICChAAGIAEGLEDGArCAgsQABiABBixAxiDAcICBBAAGB7CAgYQABgIGB6YAwCIBgGSBwIxMaAHrDmyBwIxMLgHiQQ&amp;sclient=img\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Urban disaster damage</a>” or similar in image search engine</li>\n<li>Feelings: Devestation, vulnerability, loss, fear</li>\n<li><em>Unsafe Streets</em></li>\n<li>Search “<a href=\"https://www.google.co.uk/search?q=dark+city+street&amp;sca_esv=45c41d3e543101a5&amp;udm=2&amp;biw=1200&amp;bih=728&amp;ei=D8_ZZ4O3OrTfp84P96m04Q0&amp;ved=0ahUKEwjD-pT-s5SMAxW078kDHfcULdwQ4dUDCBE&amp;uact=5&amp;oq=dark+city+street&amp;gs_lp=EgNpbWciEGRhcmsgY2l0eSBzdHJlZXQyBRAAGIAEMgQQABgeMgQQABgeMgQQABgeMgQQABgeMgYQABgIGB4yBhAAGAgYHjIGEAAYCBgeMgYQABgIGB5I0xFQhwNYjxBwA3gAkAEAmAE6oAHoBaoBAjE2uAEDyAEA-AEBmAIQoAKoBsICChAAGIAEGEMYigXCAggQABiABBixA8ICCxAAGIAEGLEDGIMBwgIOEAAYgAQYsQMYgwEYigXCAgQQABgDmAMAiAYBkgcCMTagB7xOsgcCMTa4B6gG&amp;sclient=img\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Dark city street</a>” or similar in image search engine</li>\n<li>Feelings: Fear, unsafe, vulnerability.</li>\n</ul><br>Introduce free verse poetry as a form that breaks away from traditional rules of rhyme and meter. It allows poets to express themselves with greater flexibility and freedom.<br>Key points:\n<ul>\n<li><em>No Set Rules</em></li>\n<li>Unlike traditional poetry, free verse doesn’t follow a strict rhyme scheme or meter (a pattern of stressed and unstressed syllables).</li>\n<li>This freedom allows poets to focus on the content and emotional impact of their words.</li>\n<li><em>Emphasis on Natural Rhythm</em></li>\n<li>Free verse often mimics the natural rhythms of speech.</li>\n<li>Line breaks and stanza breaks are used to create pauses and emphasize certain words or phrases.</li>\n<li><em>Focus on Imagery and Language</em></li>\n<li>Free verse poets often use vivid imagery, sensory details, and strong verbs to create a powerful impression.</li>\n<li>The way words are arranged on the page can also contribute to the poem’s meaning and impact.</li>\n<li><em>Capturing Raw Emotion</em></li>\n<li>Because of its flexibility, free verse is well-suited for expressing raw emotions and unfiltered experiences.</li>\n<li>It can capture the complexities of urban life, from the excitement of a bustling street to the loneliness of a crowded city.</li>\n<li><em>Examples</em></li>\n<li>Langston Hughes: Known for his powerful free verse poems that captured the experiences of African Americans in urban settings.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/46480/i-hear-america-singing\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>I Hear America Singing</em></a><em>,</em> Walt Whitman</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/150995/dreams-5d767850da976\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>Dreams</em></a><em>,</em> Langston Hughes</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/46548/harlem\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>Harlem</em></a><em>,</em> Langston Hughes</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poetrymagazine/poems/12840/chicago\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>Chicago</em></a><em>,</em> Carl Sandburg</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poetrymagazine/poems/12675/in-a-station-of-the-metro\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>In a Station of the Metro</em></a><em>,</em> Ezra Pound</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poetrymagazine/poems/162736/the-photographer\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>The Photographer</em></a><em>,</em> Madeleine Cravens</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poetrymagazine/poems/155006/sky-5fd041b4bcda0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>Sky</em></a><em>,</em> Emily Spencer</li>\n<li>Emphasize that free verse is about expressing oneself authentically.</li>\n</ul></p>"} />

	<CustomSection title={"Exploring Global Goal 11"} content={"<p>Divide students into small groups (3-4 students). Assign each group one or two specific targets from Global Goal 11, or have them focus on the Goal holistically.<br>Ask each group to:\n<ul>\n<li>Read and discuss their assigned goal/targets and indicators.</li>\n<li>Identify key words and phrases that resonate with them.</li>\n<li>Brainstorm real-life examples or scenarios related to their targets.</li>\n</ul><br>Examples:\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Target 11.1</strong> <em>(Affordable Housing)</em></li>\n<li>Visible homelessness in city centers.</li>\n<li>Rapidly increasing rent prices making it difficult for young adults to find housing.</li>\n<li>Informal settlements lacking basic sanitation and running water.</li>\n<li>Gentrification displacing long-time residents.</li>\n<li>Substandard apartment buildings with mold or structural issues.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.2</strong> <em>(Sustainable Transportation)</em></li>\n<li>Overcrowded buses/trains/public transportation during rush hour.</li>\n<li>Long commute times due to traffic congestion.</li>\n<li>Lack of accessible public transportation for people with disabilities.</li>\n<li>Unsafe bike lanes or pedestrian walkways.</li>\n<li>High cost of public ransportations.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.3</strong> <em>(Inclusive Urbanization)</em></li>\n<li>Lack of community input in urban development projects.</li>\n<li>Unequal distribution of resources and amenities in different neighborhoods.</li>\n<li>Rapid urban sprawl leading to environmental degradation.</li>\n<li>City planning that does not address the needs of diverse populations.</li>\n<li>Developers building new structures without regard to the effects on the local community.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.4</strong> <em>(Cultural Heritage)</em></li>\n<li>Demolition of historic buildings for new development.</li>\n<li>Neglect of cultural landmarks due to lack of funding.</li>\n<li>Pollution damaging natural ecosystems within cities.</li>\n<li>Loss of traditional cultural practices in urban areas.</li>\n<li>Lack of funding for local museums and historical sites.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.5</strong> <em>(Disaster Resilience)</em></li>\n<li>Flooding in low-lying areas due to inadequate drainage systems.</li>\n<li>Damage to infrastructure from earthquakes or storms.</li>\n<li>Lack of emergency preparedness plans in vulnerable communities.</li>\n<li>Economic hardship following a natural disaster.</li>\n<li>Damage to homes due to wildfires.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.6</strong> <em>(Environmental Impact)</em></li>\n<li>Poor air quality due to vehicle emissions and industrial pollution.</li>\n<li>Overflowing landfills and inadequate waste management.</li>\n<li>Lack of recycling and composting initiatives.</li>\n<li>Urban heat island effect due to excessive concrete and asphalt.</li>\n<li>Pollution of local waterways.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.7</strong> <em>(Green Spaces)</em></li>\n<li>Lack of parks or recreational areas in certain neighborhoods.</li>\n<li>Unsafe public spaces due to crime or inadequate lighting.</li>\n<li>Limited accessibility for people with disabilities in public parks.</li>\n<li>Harassment of women or marginalized groups in public spaces.</li>\n<li>Lack of public restrooms.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.a</strong> <em>(Urban-Rural Links)</em></li>\n<li>Lack of transportation between cities and surrounding rural areas.</li>\n<li>Unequal access to resources and opportunities between urban and rural populations.</li>\n<li>Environmental degradation in rural areas due to urban expansion.</li>\n<li>Poor communication between city and rural governments.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.b</strong> <em>(Disaster Risk Reduction)</em></li>\n<li>Lack of coordinated disaster risk reduction strategies.</li>\n<li>Inadaquate climate change adaptation plans.</li>\n<li>Failure to implement sustainable building codes.</li>\n<li>Local governments ignoring national disaster risk reduction strategies.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.c</strong> <em>(Sustainable Buildings in Least Developed Countries)</em></li>\n<li>Lack of access to sustainable building materials in developing countries.</li>\n<li>Inadequate funding for infrastructure development in least developed countries.</li>\n<li>Buildings collapsing due to poor construction and lack of regulation.</li>\n<li>A lack of skilled labor to create resilient buildings.</li>\n<li>Relate the goal/targets to their own lived experience.</li>\n</ul><br>Leading Questions:\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Target 11.1</strong> <em>(Affordable Housing)</em></li>\n<li>Have you ever wondered what it’s like to struggle to find a safe and affordable place to live?</li>\n<li>When you walk through your city, what feelings arise when you see people experiencing homelessness?</li>\n<li>Have you noticed any changes in your neighborhood, like older buildings being replaced with expensive new ones, and wondered who can afford the new places?</li>\n<li>Do you believe that everyone in our community has equal access to housing that is both safe and healthy?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.2</strong> <em>(Sustainable Transportation)</em></li>\n<li>Have you ever felt the frustration of being later because of traffic or a delayed bus? What impact does that have on your day?</li>\n<li>When you’re walking or biking, do you ever feel unsafe? What makes you feel that way?</li>\n<li>Do you think the cost of public transportation is fair and accessible to everyone in our community?</li>\n<li>Have you ever witnessed or experienced a situation where someone with a disability couldn’t easily use public transit? What challenges did they face?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.3</strong> <em>(Inclusive Urbanization)</em></li>\n<li>Do you feel like your opinions matter when decisions are made about your neighborhood or city?</li>\n<li>Are there parts of our city that seem to be overlooked or lacking resources? What might be the reasons for that?</li>\n<li>Have you ever had the opportunity to participate in a community meeting about a local development project? What was that experience like?</li>\n<li>As our city grows, do you think it’s doing so in a way that will be sustainable for future generations?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.4</strong> <em>(Cultural Heritage)</em></li>\n<li>Are there any places in our city that you feel are important to preserve because of their history or culture?</li>\n<li>Have you noticed any changes in our city that might be threatening our historical landmarks or natural spaces?</li>\n<li>Do you think our city does enough to protect and celebrate its unique history and natural environment?</li>\n<li>How often do you take advantage of local museums, or historical sites?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.5</strong> <em>(Disaster Resilience)</em></li>\n<li>Have you ever experienced the impact of a natural disaster, either directly or indirectly?</li>\n<li>Does your family or school have a plan in case of an emergency or natural disaster?</li>\n<li>Do you feel confident that our city is prepared to handle potential disasters?</li>\n<li>If a flood, earthquake, or other disaster occured, do you know what steps you would take to stay safe?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.6</strong> <em>(Environmental Impact)</em></li>\n<li>When you look at the sky in our city, do you ever notice signs of air pollution?</li>\n<li>How often do you think about where your trash goes? Do you participate in recycling or composting?</li>\n<li>Do you believe our city is taking enough action to protect our environment?</li>\n<li>Have you ever noticed that some parts of our city feel much hotter than others, even on the same day? Why might that be?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.7</strong> <em>(Green Spaces)</em></li>\n<li>When you’re in a park or public space, do you always feel safe and comfortable?</li>\n<li>Are there enough places for young people to have fun and be active in our community?</li>\n<li>Do you think that all public spaces in our city are welcoming and accessible to everyone, regardless of their background or abilities?</li>\n<li>Have you or someone you know ever felt uncomfortable or unsafe in a public space? What happened?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.a</strong> <em>(Urban-Rural Links)</em></li>\n<li>Do you have connections to people who live in rural areas outside our city? What are their lives like?</li>\n<li>Have you noticed any differences in the opportunities available to people in cities versus those in rural areas?</li>\n<li>Do you think that cities and rural areas could benefit from working together more closely? How?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.b</strong> <em>(Disaster Risk Reduction)</em></li>\n<li>Do you know if our city has plans in place to handle emergencies or natural disasters? How effective do you think they are?</li>\n<li>Do you believe our city is taking the threat of climate change seriously? What actions are they taking?</li>\n<li>Do you feel that our local government is doing everything that it can to keep us safe and prepared?</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.c</strong> <em>(Sustainable Buildings in Least Developed Countries)</em></li>\n<li>Do you think everyone around the world deserves to live in a safe and well-built home?</li>\n<li>When you see news reports of buildings collapsing, what thoughts come to mind?</li>\n<li>How does global inequality affect the ability of some countries to build safe and resilient infrastructure?</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Free Verse Creation"} content={"<p>Explain that students will write a free verse poem that captures their understanding and feelings about their assigned goal/target(s).<br>Encourage students to:\n<ul>\n<li>Focus on vivid imagery and sensory details.</li>\n<li>Use strong verbs and evocative language.</li>\n<li>Experiment with line breaks, spacing, and word choice.</li>\n<li>Encourage the use of the five senses in their poems.</li>\n</ul><br>Provide examples of prompts if needed:\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Target 11.1</strong> <em>(Affordable Housing)</em></li>\n<li>Describe the feeling of carrying all your belongings in a shopping cart, searching for a place to sleep.</li>\n<li>Capture the silence of an empty apartment, where a family used to live before they were evicted.</li>\n<li>Write about the contrast between the warmth of a home and the chill of a city street at night.</li>\n<li>Imagine the texture of a makeshift wall in an informal settlement, and what stories it could tell.</li>\n<li>Describe the feeling of finally getting the keys to your first affordable apartment.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.2</strong> <em>(Sustainable Transportation)</em></li>\n<li>Write about the rhythm of a train ride, and the faces you see through the window.</li>\n<li>Capture the frustration of a traffic jam, where time seems to stand still.</li>\n<li>Describe the joy of riding a bicycle through a city on a sunn day.</li>\n<li>Imagine the struggle of navigating a crowded subway with a disability.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of finally arriving at your destination after a long commute.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.3</strong> <em>(Inclusive Urbanization)</em></li>\n<li>Describe the feeling of standing in a room where decisions are made that affect your neighborhood, but you have no voice.</li>\n<li>Capture the sound of bulldozers tearing down old buildings to make way for new developments.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of seeing your community’s needs reflected in a city plan.</li>\n<li>Imagine a city where every resident has a say in how their neighborhood is designed.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of seeing a community garden grow in a previously neglected space.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.4</strong> <em>(Cultural Heritage)</em></li>\n<li>Describe the feeling of touching the worn stone of an ancient monument.</li>\n<li>Capture the sound of a traditional song being sung in a city square.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of watching a natural habitat disappear as a city expands.</li>\n<li>Imagine the stories held within the walls of a historic building, now slated for demolition.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of discovering a hidden natural oasis within a bustling city.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.5</strong> <em>(Disaster Resilience)</em></li>\n<li>Describe the feeling of the ground shaking during an earthquake.</li>\n<li>Capture the sound of sirens wailing as emergency vehicles race through the streets.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of searching for loved ones in the aftermath of a disaster.</li>\n<li>Imagine the devastation of a community after a flood, and the struggle to rebuild.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of community members helping each other after a disaster.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.6</strong> <em>(Environmental Impact)</em></li>\n<li>Describe the feeling of breathing in polluted air on a hot summer day.</li>\n<li>Capture the sight of overflowing landfills and the stench of rotting garbage.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of planting a tree in a concrete jungle.</li>\n<li>Imagine a city where clean energy powers every home and building.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of watching clean water flow into a previously polluted river.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.7</strong> <em>(Green Spaces)</em></li>\n<li>Describe the feeling of sitting on a park bench, watching people from all walks of life interact.</li>\n<li>Capture the sound of children laughing and playing in a public playground.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of walking alone at night in an unsafe neighborhood.</li>\n<li>Imagine a city where every park is accessible to people with disabilities.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of attending a community event in a vibrant public square.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.a</strong> <em>(Urban-Rural Links)</em></li>\n<li>Describe the feeling of traveling from a bustling city to a quiet rural town.</li>\n<li>Capture the sound of farm animals and the smell of fresh produce at a farmers’ market.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of seeing urban sprawl encroach on farmland.</li>\n<li>Imagine a city where urban and rural communities work together to share resources.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of eating food grown in a local community garden.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.b</strong> <em>(Disaster Risk Reduction)</em></li>\n<li>Describe the feeling of attending a city council meeting where disaster preparedness plans are discussed.</li>\n<li>Capture the sound of construction workers building a resilient building designed to withstand natural disasters.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of seeing a city implement sustainable building codes.</li>\n<li>Imagine a city where local governments work together to implement national disaster risk reduction strategies.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of participating in a community drill for a potential natural disaster.</li>\n<li><strong>Target 11.c</strong> <em>(Sustainable Buildings in Least Developed Countries)</em></li>\n<li>Describe the feeling of living in a home built with substandard materials, fearing its collapse.</li>\n<li>Capture the sound of workers using local materials to build a sustainable school.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of seeing a community receive international aid to rebuild after a disaster.</li>\n<li>Imagine a world wehre all buildings are built to withstand natural disasters, regardless of location.</li>\n<li>Write about the feeling of learning new sustainable building techniques from a visiting expert.</li>\n</ul><br>Circulate the room, offering guidance and encouragement.</p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Sharing and Discussion"} content={"<p>Invite students to share their poems, with their small group or the entire class (or, if time does not allow, hand in for review).<br>After each poem, encourage brief, positive feedback and discussion.<br>Ask questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>What images or feelings did the poem evoke for you?</li>\n<li>How does this poem connect to Global Goal 11?</li>\n<li>What can we learn from this poem about the challenges and opportunities in our cities?</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Reflection and Summary"} content={"<p>Have students reflect on their learning experience through discussion or writing.<br>Ask guiding questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>How did writing in free verse - with its flexibility and emphasis on natural rhythm - help you express your unique vision and feelings about sustainable cities and communities?</li>\n<li>What did you learn about the power of vivid imagery and sensory details in making a poem about urban challenges or opportunities feel real and impactful?</li>\n<li>Did the process of crafting your free verse poem change your perspective on how poetry can communicate complex social and environmental issues like those in Global Goal 11?</li>\n<li>What did you discover about your own creative voice when given the freedom to write without traditional poetic constraints?</li>\n<li>How can poetry, as an art form, help to humanize statistics or complex urban planning concepts related to sustainable cities?</li>\n<li>How did the diverse poems shared by the class highlight the many different facets of sustainable urban development (e.g., housing, transport, green spaces, disaster resilience)?</li>\n<li>Did any specific poem or the imagery within it make you think differently about a challenge or opportunity in your own city or community related to Global Goal 11?</li>\n<li>How does a poetic lens help us consider the emotional and human impact of urban planning and development?</li>\n<li>Did writing free verse about Global Goal 11 spark any personal connections or reflections on your own experiences living in or observing urban environments?</li>\n<li>What emotions did you connect with while writing your poem, and how might those emotions motivate you to take action for sustainable cities?</li>\n<li>How has this lesson influenced your thinking about your own role in shaping the future of urban spaces?</li>\n</ul></p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Assessment"} content={"<ul>\n<li>Consistent and enthusiastic involvement in all phases of the lesson, including the initial brainstorming, understanding free verse techniques, the individual writing process, and active participation in discussions (both small group and whole class).</li>\n<li>Comprehension of Global Goal 11, targets and core concepts.This will be evidenced through the thematic content and symbolism within the free verse poem(s) and the verbal explanations.</li>\n<li>Originality and effectiveness in applying free verse elements such as vivid imagery, sensory details, strong verbs, impactful language, and intentional line breaks to convey the message about sustainable cities.</li>\n<li>How clearly and powerfully the finished free verse poem communicates its intended message about Global Goal 11. Ddi the poem successfully evoke thought or emotion in the reader/listener?</li>\n<li>Quality of the writing craft, including word choice, descriptive power, and the creation of atmosphere, demonstrating attention to poetic language.</li>\n<li>Ability to articulate creative choices and interpret and provide thoughtful feedback on classmates’ poems, connecting them to Global Goal 11 themes.</li>\n<li>Nuance and depth of understanding demonstrated in reflections, particularly concerning the role of poetry in advocating for sustainable development and the complexities of urban challenges.</li>\n</ul>"} {sdgColor} />

</div>
